<subSubSection id="C304DE8BFF97FFB578D8F3D8FDF8FCC5" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA18D00FF97FFB578D8F3D8FDF8FCC5" blockId="24.[128,654,213,884]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
REMARKS: The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1EF683FF97FFB579E4F3D9FDB4FE69" box="[416,557,449,472]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Coridromius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96A5112FF97FFB579E4F3D9FDB4FE69" box="[416,557,449,472]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Coridromius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized by the unique body shape, extremely swollen hind femora and highly specialized male genitalia. While several species are easily identifiable by coloration and body shape, others are sometimes more difficult to place. For most species the male genitalia can typically be examined in situ, but often one must remove female specimens from points or remove the hemelytra in order to expose possible paragenital modifications, which have always been found on the right side of the abdomen. The following key is intended to be used with both sexes, except in those species that are known by one sex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
